    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="335"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d335">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.11 T 41/8</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor for the Department of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lansing</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to President <persName type="to"
                            >Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 10, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. President</hi>: I enclose the telegrams received
                    from Consul General Skinner regarding the sinking of the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Falaba</hi>.<note n="23" xml:id="d335fn1">
                        <ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_359">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, pp. 359</ref>, <ref
                            target="frus1915Supp#pg_362">362</ref>, <ref
                            target="frus1915Supp#pg_364">364</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The significant fact to my mind is that the submarine’s commander allowed ten
                    minutes for the crew and passengers to leave the vessel, showing that he did not
                    act on the suspicion that the vessel was armed and might attack him. If he had
                    allowed no time for escape, he might enter that plea, but, since he gave <hi
                        rend="underline">some</hi> time, he should have given sufficient.</p>
                <p>It seems to me that the question of arming British vessels, or Germany’s belief
                    that it is being done, disappears from the <hi rend="italic">Falaba</hi>
                    case.</p>
                <p>Very sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
